01:18Z","sectionName":"Society","sectionId":"society","id":"society/2014/mar/17/ebbsfleet-garden-city-housing-osborne","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3njxa","standfirst":"Despite George Osborne's promise of 15,000 new homes, not everyone has greeted the announcement with enthusiasm","hasStoryPackage":"true","body":"<p>Few people seem quite as excited by the chancellor's announcement that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/16/george-osborne-garden-city-ebbsfleet-budget\" title=\"\">Ebbsfleet is to blossom into Britain's first new garden city for almost 100 years</a> as the chancellor himself.</p><p>\"It is not something this country has attempted for decades,\" George Osborne told Andrew Marr on Sunday. \"Britain has to up its ambition, Britain has to up its game, Britain has to earn its way in the world.\"</p><p>It's fair to say, then, that there's now a bit of pressure on Ebbsfleet, which sits amid green fields and grey ribbons of dual carriageway in a corner of Kent that is – as the ubiquitous posters remind us – a mere 17 minutes from London by train.</p><p>Yet despite the chancellor's legacy-heavy talk and its attendant promise of 15,000 new homes in the south-east, not all those who live and work in the area have greeted the announcement with giddy enthusiasm.</p><p>\"No one's really bothered about it,\" said Martin Allen, landlord of the Sun pub in nearby Swanscombe. \"But the traffic flow is going to get even worse than it is now. It doesn't bother me, but if people come in here to drink – especially the workmen – they'll be welcome.\"</p><p>His wife, Natalie, was scarcely more effusive. \"We're used to it, with Ebbsfleet [International station] being built and Bluewater, so people are used to the disruption,\" she said.</p><p>Sue Martin, who lives in nearby Greenhithe but works at the Ebbsfleet Academy in Swanscombe, welcome the jobs and the homes the project would bring but was also worried about the roads. \"We're already clogged up and we don't need any more traffic,\" she said. \"Between October and February – because of the run-up to Christmas and then the January sales – the roads round Bluewater are jammed.\"</p><p>Their underwhelmed response is not wholly surprising. As well as the high-speed rail link, the shopping centre and the new garden city – not to mention the ambitious plans for a £2bn Paramount theme park in the area – Swanscombe is already the site of the 1,035-acre Castle Hill development, which will bring 150 new houses. The two-word slogans that decorate the multi-coloured fence enclosing the development ooze comfortable, commuter-belt aspiration: \"Develop &amp; Grow\"; \"Family &amp; Friends\", \"Lakes &amp; Parks\", and, rather more abstractly, \"Here &amp; There\".</p><p>Reece Henderson, a 30-year-old HGV driver who lives in Swanscombe, felt the chancellor's plan was a pragmatic one: \"With the amount of houses that are needed, it has to be done whether people like it or not.\"</p><p>Potential pockets of nimbyism aside, though, there seems to be little opposition to the new city, the proposed creation of which comes at a time when <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/17/hs2-benefits-north-six-years-earlier-chairman\" title=\"\">the government is keen to highlight the benefits of high speed rail link</a>. The only question is how new Osborne's venture really is.</p><p>John Burden, the Labour leader of nearby Gravesham borough council, knew nothing of the garden city plan until he saw it announced on Sunday morning.</p><p>While he had yet to see the detail of the proposals, he said, they seemed in line with the planning permission that was granted a decade ago.</p><p>\"If the scheme is to build the houses in the Eastern Quarry – which is a longstanding planning permission – then I think it's a very good scheme and one that will benefit the area, particularly if it coincides with the building of the Paramount theme resort,\" he said. \"It would be very good for the area.\"</p><p>A spokesman for the Treasury said that local authorities had been consulted over then plans, adding that the chancellor's decision to use an urban development corporation (UDC) to drive the development of Ebbsfleet would ensure that everyone was given a say in the project.</p><p>Jeremy Kite, the Conservative leader of Dartford borough council (who was tipped off about the announcement on Saturday afternoon), felt the chancellor deserved praise for tackling the housing crisis.</p><p>\"The simple fact is that if you're interested in giving people houses, the key is whether there's any houses on the site,\" he said.</p><p>\"And the answer at the minute is that after eight years, there aren't any. It's all very well to say, 'We had a plan' and 'It's not a new plan' - but that plan didn't work and frankly it wasn't capable of being driven over the line.\"</p><p>Anyway, he added, the garden city would be far bigger than any previous planned housing projects and could help push through the construction of Paramount Park.</p><p>Both Burden and Sir Merrick Cockell, the chair of the Local Government Association, are worried by the involvement of an unelected UDC, but Kite believes the quango may succeed where other bodies have failed by moving swiftly past the planning phase and into the building one. Arguments over whether the garden city is an old idea or a new one were, he said, beside the point.</p><p>\"For me, this is about the long-term issue of delivery of housing. I think if we're serious about providing housing for people, sooner or later someone's got to build the buggers.\"</p>","headline":"Ebbsfleet: new garden city but the same old worries","trailText":"Despite George Osborne's promise of 15,000 new homes, not everyone has greeted the announcement with enthusiasm","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/17/1395097204627/Castle-Hill-development-s-001.jpg","wordcount":"826","liveBloggingNow":"false","co